It is with a heavy heart that we share of the tragic passing of Zamar Jones, a rising 2nd grader student at KIPP Philadelphia Elementary Academy. The entire KIPP Philadelphia community extends our heartfelt sympathies to Zamar‚Äôs family and to all their friends. Zamar was loved by his classmates and wanted to be a police officer. We will miss him very much and his memory will live on in our hearts.

Any death is difficult for young people to understand. Zamar‚Äôs death is particularly difficult due to the senseless act of gun violence. We have counselors reaching out to all the families and will have resources available to help talk about the passing of a classmate. We ask everyone to support the Zamar‚Äôs family and one another as a community of love, understanding, and support.

post_text: Today is Juneteenth, a holiday that memorializes the actual end of slavery on June 19,1865, when enslaved people in Galveston, Texas received word of their freedom, two and half years after the Emancipation Proclamation was signed. Black people have been celebrating this holiday for many years. However, we know there is much more work to do to fight anti-Blackness and creating an environment where Black people win. #Juneteenth #BlackLivesMatter #KIPPPhilly

post_text:
It is with a very heavy heart that we share the news that we lost a KIPP student last week. Rajib Ingram, a 3rd grader at KIPP Philadelphia Elementary Academy (KPEA), passed away. Rajib was silly in the best of ways. He was an avid fan of recess and a budding engineer who loved to spend his time building structures with various objects.

The entire KIPP Philadelphia community extends our heartfelt sympathies to Rajib's family and to all their friends. We will miss him very much and his memory will live on in our hearts.

KIPP would like to honor him this week by wearing blueüíô, his favorite color, to Zoom classes. We ask everyone to support Rajib's family and one another as a community of love, understanding, and support.

post_text:
üí°LEARNING TIP OF THE DAY: Help, don't hover!

For younger students, set them up in a place that you can help ensure that things are going okay. Older students will probably be able to set themselves up on their own. Once students are set up in their virtual classrooms, for both younger and older students, do your best to let them fly solo (as you would on a regular school day).

The more students can feel like they are in the classroom, the more authentically they will feel they can participate in the lesson! #KIPPPhilly #DistanceLearning #TeamAndFamily

post_text:
TO ALL KIPP PHILADELPHIA FAMILIES: As our city and country grapple with an unprecedented situation, I want to make sure we keep you as well informed as possible. We recognize the stress you are under as parents and caregivers and seek to alleviate that as much as possible through consistent communication. Thus, I am writing to inform you of today's COVID-19 updates-

1. In alignment with the School District of Philadelphia, KIPP Philadelphia Public Schools will be closed until at least March 27.
2. At this point, KIPP Philadelphia schools have no confirmed or presumptive cases of COVID-19.
3. We will be providing students with meals and learning materials next week. Please expect notification on Monday describing the pickup process.
4. To stay abreast of citywide COVID-19 updates from Mayor Kenney's office, please text COVIDPHL to 888-777.
5. Moving forward, please expect (Monday - Friday) communication from us every afternoon between 4 and 6 PM.

Sincerely,

Jessica Cunningham Akoto, CEO

post_text:
KIPP Schools wants to thank #KIPP Foundation Board Member, Martha Karsh and the Karsh Family Foundation, for their $10 million gift to endow the prestigious #STEM program at Howard University.

This gift will create an endowment of the #STEM program increasing the number of underrepresented minorities who earn a Ph.D. or MD/Ph.D. in a #STEM discipline. This gift will also create the #LomaxKIPPScholarship, in partnership with #KIPP, and in honor of #KIPP Board Member and UNCF CEO & President Dr. Michael Lomax.

Thank you to our partners for supporting to the futures of our #KIPPsters.

https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/education/largest-gift-in-howard-university-history-to-fund-science-and-technology/2020/01/21/3f40359c-3bf5-11ea-b90d-5652806c3b3a_story.htm

post_text:
Congratulations to our own Jason Smith! He is the KIPP Through College and Career Senior Director of Post-Secondary Outcomes. This summer marked the end of a yearlong fellowship for Mr. Smith. He was one of 12 Black male educators selected to be a part of the Outstanding Black Male Fellowship through a partnership with The National Network of State Teachers of the Year and the University of Phoenix. The fellowship examined why the men became educators, and what inspires them to persist through a career in education. The fellowship culminated with a paper, which you can click the link below to read more. Mr. Smith hopes the paper teaches people to engage, celebrate, and enact black male educators in a different way. #KIPPPhilly #LeadersLearning

http://www.nnstoy.org/publications/examining-career-trajectories-for-black-male-educators-in-p-12-education/

Our staff and teachers are having a blast at #KSS2019! The KIPP School Summit (KSS) is an annual gathering of the entire KIPP Team and Family to connect, learn, and share with our colleagues and friends from across the country.

KIPP School Summit 2019 is a program crafted by KIPP alumni, staff, and advisors. This year we‚Äôre going back to where it all began: Houston, TX. Today is day two of three inspiring days surrounded by 6,000 teachers, staffers, leaders, partners, and alumni as we prepare for the 2019‚Äì20 school year.

KSS 2019, also KIPP‚Äôs 25th anniversary, will be an opportunity for ALL to celebrate, learn, and grow together. KSS 2019 will be grounded entirely in the leadership and experiences of alumni. Check out more KSS stories on our Twitter & Instagram accounts.

Roland Martin and The 74 (the74million.org) invite you to attend ‚ÄúIs School Choice the Black Choice?" an education town hall aimed at helping Philadelphia parents learn how they can better access high-quality schools for their children. The event will take place on Wednesday, May 29th from 6-8pm at Mastery Charter School‚Äôs Shoemaker Campus. This event will feature prominent national and local education advocates and will offer opportunities to network with local education reform, faith, and civic groups. The event is free. Childcare will be provided.

You don‚Äôt want to miss this exciting event, so be sure to secure your spot ASAP! Register here: https://www.eventbrite.com/e/is-school-choice-the-black-choice-keeping-it-100-for-philadelphia-students-tickets-60722043266
